<font color="#FF0000">MORE COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul  9 23:02:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Cook,<br>
I am glad to have you explain in detail.  It is good to have someone new posting here on this site.  I'm sorry if my postings offended you, I just wanted you to provide more details.  Hope you stick around here, and by the way I hope you didn't think I was insulting the Marines.  I have the greatest respect for the Marine Corp, 13,000 of them were killed in Nam and they always got the job done.  As for the Liberty Bridge, Yes I do find it funny in a way, especially how the VC waited for the bridge to be fininshed and then blew it up.  I guess it would be laugh or go out of your head. It is crazy but funny &quot;Boo Koo Dinky Dau&quot; all the way.<br><br>
In regards to Vietnam, I still don't see why it was necessary.  In regards to the &quot;Cold War&quot;, there are many members of the VFW who are trying to get a medal/ribbon authorized for the time period.  I agree, that everyone who served did so in defense of America from a Communist threat.  <br><br>
I still think Vietnam was not necessary.  We could have helped the Vietnamese people with aid and training, but we as a military and nation were wrong to take over the war, a war that we didn't plan well or run well.  In the end we brought incredible weapons power to bear on a small country, spent 10 years there and lost 58,000 men (not to mention the Vietnamese casualties).  We didn't even save the Vietnamese people from a Communist faith, just prevented it for a little while longer.  I am in no way insulting the soldiers there, America fielded no finer force in its history (it took a lot to be a soldier, in a time when soldiers were not in fashion).  I think the memory of all that served needs to be preserved and remembered that most served in a unselfish manner looking to do whatever was asked of them.<br><br>
Vietnam was a mistake for this country.  It divided a generation and cost America countless lives.  I do believe our motives were unselfish.  It didn't serve to weaken Russia, their own policies coupled with their &quot;Vietnam&quot; in Afghanistan did that.  Our policy of containment just let them rot away at the core.  Vietnam was not necessary, but it is to late to argue this any further, it has happened.  Instead we all must learn from it.  The lessons to be learned from it are:<br><br>
1. Question government<br>
2.  Citizens need to stay informed about world affairs and what our government is doing.<br>
3.  The United States never fielded beter Armies than in Vietnam.<br>
4.  The United States should never engage in war without total commitment to win.<br>
5.  The America people need to lay aside differences and support the men and women of America once they are at war.  Many people of the 60's couldn't separate the war from the warrior.  They hated the war, but made a target of the warrior.  That is unforgivable.<br>
6.  Vietnam has demonstrated the grimness of war.  Previous wars had a habit of being presented in a glorious good guy/bad guy image.  Vietnam showed us the true horror of war and I hope that America has learned from that image.  War is serious and needs to be taken seriously.<br>
7.  Learn as much about a country and its people as you can before deploying there.      
